{{Other uses|Pigasus (disambiguation)}}
The '''Pigasus''' was used by [[John Steinbeck]] as a personal stamp with the [[Latin]] [[motto]] ''[[Ad astra (phrase)|Ad astra]] per alia porci,'' intended to mean "to the stars on the wings of a pig."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sjsu.edu/steinbeck/biography/biography_pigasus/ |title=Pigasus |publisher=Steinbeck Center}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wDCMUh6IF_4C&pg=PA296 | title=Steinbeck: A Life in Letters | editor=Elaine Steinbeck and Robert Wallstein |publisher=Penguin |date=1976 |page=296}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7enYCwAAQBAJ&pg=PR2 | title=The Portable Steinbeck |editor=Pascal Covici Jr. |publisher=Penguin |date=2012 |page=ii}}</ref>  The Latin is incorrect because "alia" means "other things,"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bMbIDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA260 |title=Latin Beyond GCSE |author=John Taylor |publisher=Bloomsbury |date=2017 |page=260}}/</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/et_alia |title=Wiktionary: alia |accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref> while "alas" would be the accusative form of "wings" after the preposition "per."<ref>{{cite web | url=https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/alas#Noun_5 |title=Wiktionary: alas |accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LK0BAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA81 |title=The Eton Latin Grammar |author=Arthur Campbell Ainger |date=1887 |page=81}}</ref>  The pigasus was supposed to symbolize Steinbeck as "earthbound but aspiring...not enough wingspread but plenty of intention."

Coincidentally, another Pigasus was a character in the [[Oz books|''Oz'' books]] written by [[Ruth Plumly Thompson]] in the 1930s.<ref>[[Jack Snow (writer)|Jack Snow]], ''Who's Who in Oz'', Chicago, Reilly & Lee, 1954; New York, Peter Bedrick Books, 1988; p. 161.</ref> Her Pigasus was also a winged pig. As with [[Pegasus]], his riders gained the gift of poesy, being magically compelled to speak in rhyming jingles while on his back.  The character first appeared in ''[[Pirates in Oz]]'' and played a major role in the plot of ''[[The Wishing Horse of Oz]]''.

